    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-16T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-16T17:00:00-05:00" n="188"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">461.11/867: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-16T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 16, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>276. Your 502, May 8, 5 p.m. Please draft a reply to the Commissariat
                    acknowledging receipt of its note of April 26 and informing it that you have
                    been instructed by your Government to state that your Government looks to the
                    Government of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics for the compensation of
                    any American nationals or firms <pb facs="0214" n="202" xml:id="pg_202"/> who
                    may have suffered losses as the result of the acts of nationalization of foreign
                    property in the territories referred to in the instruction of the Commissariat
                    for Justice of February 28 as Western Ukraine and Western Belorussiya.<note
                        n="57" xml:id="d188fn57">The Chargé in the Soviet Union reported in his
                        despatch No. 483, May 17, that a note in compliance with this instruction
                        had been addressed to the People’s Commissariat for Foreign Affairs
                        (461.11/874).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
